There probably aren't many vets who haven't heard of PTSD. There are many vets who suffered from the same. Many have or are currently working at dealing with the symptoms to accomodate with their life styles. One sure sign of the healing process after 30 plus years is being able to listen to those that opposed the war or took other stances where the war was concerned. Agreement is not warranted nor necessary. Constructive dialog is.<br><br>
In the past couple of weeks, I have lamented the outcropping of anon's who use their invisibility to strike at the current crop of vets. I have seen the current crop of vets strike out at these(this) anon(s) using personal attacks to demean their arguments.<br><br>
In a common debate, heated arguments are not uncommon. Personal attacks in themselves are, however, totally useless and destructive, not just to the individual whom it is directed, but to this site as well. This is not to say that I have not contributed my share.<br><br>
I have gone back to the &quot;Protestor&quot; thread and reviewed what was written. The likes of T. Crenshaw, J. Riddle, J. Wrinkler, M. Toliver, A. Hernandez, Gerald Ney, Tanker and many more have contributed many thought provoking insights. I lament their not being on this site any longer.<br><br>
I believe its time to begin being inclusive again and stop the behavior which excludes all but the handful of vets that have dominated these pages these last few months.<br><br>
Or else this site will surely die.<br><br>

